Capstone Milestone Report

Oliver Hofkens

10/22/2017

This milestone report will provide some basic data exploration, and outline the process of cleaning the data before building a model. Four datasets containing blog posts, news articles and tweets were made available: German, English, Finnish, and Russian. I chose to explore the English dataset.

Data Exploration

We are presented with 200MB of blog post text, 196MB of news articles, and 159MB of tweets. Those sizes may not say much, so let’s look at some actual counts:

# Read the corpus in with tm, then transform it to a Quanteda corpus.
corp <-VCorpus(DirSource('data/raw/final/en_US', encoding="UTF-8"), readerControl = list(reader = readPlain))
corp <- corpus(corp)
nSentences <- nsentence(corp)
nWords <- ntoken(corp)
  • The blogposts contain a total of 2077533 sentences, containing 42840097 words.
  • The news articles contain 1868674 sentences, with 39918312 words.
  • The tweets contain a total of 2598128 sentences, containing 36719689 words.

Even though the tweets dataset is the smallest, it contains the largest number of sentences, with a relative low amount of words. This can be attributed to the maximum of 140 characters in a tweet.

Let’s take a closer look at our data, which words appear the most in each of the datasets?

docFeatureMatrix <- dfm(corp)
textplot_wordcloud(docFeatureMatrix, comparison = TRUE)
